snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Alton,
Thank you for this nice, fairly simple cookie recipe, and easy to follow instructions.
Also, I fondly remember how you used to say, when you still had Good Eats, "Oh bother!!".
Well, guess what?! Tonight, when I was watching the old black-n-white episodes of Andy Griffith, there was a guest appearance of the actor that voices Winnie the Pooh!! He's the one who says, "Oh bother!". (Sterling Holloway).
My daughter noticed him right away, she exclaimed, "that's Winnie the Pooh!!!"
We watch all the old reruns of the old shows every night.
Check out MeTV channel, Antenna TV, and CoziTV. All of these channels have the old cherished favorites. You and Elizabeth can watch all these, look on the guide, instead of drinking yourself into oblivion, or manically making video, after video!! Lol.
Don't forget Perry Mason, Twilight Zone, Alfred Hitchcock, Mannix, Cannon, Barnaby Jones, Dragnet, Adam 12, etc.

At night, we watch Andy Griffith, Gomer Pyle, Green Acres, Hogun's Heros, Perry Mason, ....
In the morning, it's I Love Lucy, The Beverly Hillbillys, My Three Sons, Leave It to Beaver, ....
That Girl, on AntennaTV, and Charlies Angels, and Bionic Woman, don't forget, Father Knows Best, at 6am-7am.
And the original Starsky and Hutch, every Saturday afternoon, on CoziTV.

"And just one more thing", (Columbo)

*enjoy. Lol. 😀❤

snippet.textDisplay:
1 cup smooth peanut butter
¼ cup packed light brown sugar
½ cup granulated sugar
1 large egg
1 teaspoon baking soda
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
¼ teaspoon kosher salt

Heat the oven to 350°F. Line to half sheet pans with parchment paper and set aside.
Beat together the peanut butter, brown sugar, and granulated sugar until well combined with a wooden spoon in a large bowl. Add the egg, baking soda, vanilla, and salt and beat until well combined.
Roll the dough into 1-ounce balls, place 8 per prepared sheet pan, then flatten with the tines of a fork. Bake for 10 minutes, or until the cookies look dry and are just lightly browned. Cool the cookies for 2 minutes on the sheet pans.
snippet.textOriginal:
1 cup smooth peanut butter
¼ cup packed light brown sugar
½ cup granulated sugar
1 large egg
1 teaspoon baking soda
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
¼ teaspoon kosher salt

Heat the oven to 350°F. Line to half sheet pans with parchment paper and set aside.
Beat together the peanut butter, brown sugar, and granulated sugar until well combined with a wooden spoon in a large bowl. Add the egg, baking soda, vanilla, and salt and beat until well combined.
Roll the dough into 1-ounce balls, place 8 per prepared sheet pan, then flatten with the tines of a fork. Bake for 10 minutes, or until the cookies look dry and are just lightly browned. Cool the cookies for 2 minutes on the sheet pans.

snippet.textDisplay: I know this recipe is delicious, and not only because Alton. I know it's good because I prefer a similar recipe, from Smitten Kitchen https://smittenkitchen.com/2015/10/salted-peanut-butter-cookies/. With only brown sugar, the cookies are darker, which looks nicer IMO, and I like the heavier molasses note. The salt is sprinkled on top, instead of mixed in, for that sharp salty hit. Also, I don't like flattening the cookies, since leaving them in scoop form makes for a softer interior. You need to put the scooped dough in the freezer for a few minutes, or they'll flatten out too much; you also need a bit more oven time. One important note, for both recipes, is that if the edges of the cookies become brown, they are likely overdone. I take them out when they're still pretty soft; even after they cool, they stay chewy. Keep healthy, everyone.
